[{"question":"So what is your reaction to the President\u0027s speech tonight?","answer":"Well, I think the President went to step by step in directly responding to the concerns of the American people.","docId":"130910pmt","qSentId":4,"aSentId":5},{"question":"But he\u0027s boxed himself into a really difficult corner now, isn\u0027t he?","answer":"Well, look, I believe that number one we\u0027ll have to see whether this diplomatic effort is real.","docId":"130910pmt","qSentId":17,"aSentId":18},{"question":"It\u0027s pretty rum state of affairs, isn\u0027t it?","answer":"Well, look, Piers.","docId":"130910pmt","qSentId":23,"aSentId":24},{"question":"Are these two things slightly paralyzing the President right now?","answer":"I don\u0027t know if they\u0027re paralyzing him now, but it seems like they did for a while.","docId":"130910pmt","qSentId":77,"aSentId":78},{"question":"How does that work in reality?","answer":"Well, it\u0027s going to be tough.","docId":"130910pmt","qSentId":87,"aSentId":88},{"question":"Is that plausible?","answer":"AY: It\u0027s not at all plausible.","docId":"130910pmt","qSentId":105,"aSentId":106},{"question":"Do they buy it in from places like Russia, where do they get such a large amount of sarin or whatever it may be?","answer":"They got the basic technology of how to make it and how to made it to rockets, artillery, aerial bombs during the Soviet Union and from Czechoslovakia.","docId":"130910pmt","qSentId":115,"aSentId":116},{"question":"Tell us what you liked about the President speech first?","answer":"Well, you know, I think he made a good point that atrocities occurred to know that there was something awful that happened, the gas attacks, you can\u0027t watch them without having a great deal of sympathy for the people.","docId":"130910pmt","qSentId":137,"aSentId":138},{"question":"Bashar al-Assad?","answer":"Yes.","docId":"130910pmt","qSentId":140,"aSentId":141},{"question":"Do you think he should go in there and try to kill him?","answer":"Well, the thing is, is that I think his plan now is to spare Assad to leave the regime in place, but at the same time he says, someone must pay for breaking this international norm, but he\u0027s really not willing to actually make Assad pay.","docId":"130910pmt","qSentId":143,"aSentId":144},{"question":"Targeted assassination?","answer":"Well, I\u0027m not really saying that, what I\u0027m arguing is this that what the President has plan is not going to accomplish what he says he\u0027s going to accomplish which is to punish Assad for this.","docId":"130910pmt","qSentId":147,"aSentId":148},{"question":"You hope that this Russian initiative works, right?","answer":"I do.","docId":"130910pmt","qSentId":151,"aSentId":152},{"question":"So, you welcome the President\u0027s decision to go to Congress?","answer":"Yes, absolutely, that\u0027s the constitutional manner you have to have Congressional authority before you go to war unless we\u0027re in imminent danger.","docId":"130910pmt","qSentId":168,"aSentId":169},{"question":"Is there any Congressional authority, any resolution you could vote for?","answer":"If American interests were involved, American soldiers, American business, American citizens, a direct threat to an ally, a NATO ally, Israel, all of those things there\u0027s a lot of the American interest in the Middle East that I would say ...","docId":"130910pmt","qSentId":170,"aSentId":171},{"question":"Why do you -- explain that?","answer":"So, far Assad is not -- he\u0027s preoccupied in his own country and he has another chance to reach out or lash out in other countries, if we bomb him or if we corner him I think there\u0027s more of a chance that he lashes out against Israel.","docId":"130910pmt","qSentId":174,"aSentId":175},{"question":"AUL: When you saw your people -- repeat the last part of that?","answer":"Don\u0027t use gas.","docId":"130910pmt","qSentId":183,"aSentId":184}]